  <article class="post-content">
    <img src="/assets/images/scribblinggeek-the-pinnacle-2640724.jpg" alt="The Pinnacle@Duxton — iconic Singapore HDB development representing the peak of public housing" loading="eager" decoding="async" />

    <p>2025 was the year HDB resale stopped being a "ceiling" market and became a genuine supply-and-demand story. Million-dollar flats stopped making headlines because they stopped being unusual. Here's what actually happened — and what it means for 2026 buyers and sellers.</p>

    <h2>The numbers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Median resale price up ~5.4% YoY.</strong> A measured climb, not a runaway.</li>
      <li><strong>Million-dollar transactions: roughly 2.8% of all resale volume.</strong> Up from 1.9% in 2024 — concentrated in mature estates and well-located 5-room/executive flats.</li>
      <li><strong>MOP supply increased by ~12%.</strong> A wave of 2020-era BTOs hit the resale market as their MOP cleared.</li>
      <li><strong>Average days-on-market dropped to ~38 days.</strong> Demand outpaced listing.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What's driving demand</h2>
    <p>Three forces:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Upgraders timing the move.</strong> Many couples who got BTOs around 2020 are reaching the upgrade window — and a fair number are choosing to "upgrade in place" by selling and buying a larger resale rather than going private.</li>
      <li><strong>Extended lease purchasers.</strong> With lease-decay concerns easing in selected mature estates (thanks to VERS and SERS clarity), buyers are returning to flats with 70-80 years remaining.</li>
      <li><strong>Cash-rich downsizers.</strong> Right-sizers exiting larger private property for centrally-located resale with less maintenance overhead.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The 2026 outlook</h2>
    <p>I expect:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Continued mid-single-digit price growth</strong> — barring a cooling-measure intervention</li>
      <li><strong>MOP supply easing slightly</strong> — fewer 2021-era BTOs reach MOP in 2026</li>
      <li><strong>Million-dollar share creeping up</strong> — likely toward 3.5–4% by year-end</li>
      <li><strong>Increased policy attention</strong> if growth accelerates — watch the August NDR for any signal</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What buyers should do</h2>
    <p>If you're buying resale in 2026:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Don't anchor on 2024 prices.</strong> They're stale.</li>
      <li><strong>Move on the right unit, not the cheapest.</strong> In a tight market, layout and location compound; PSF discounts on bad layouts don't.</li>
      <li><strong>Have your IPA ready before you offer.</strong> Sellers in mature estates are seeing multiple offers and will favour buyers who can move fast.</li>
    </ul>

